Docker swarm has its own load balancer, network and DNS system. If you want to use your own balancer there is no reason to define IP addresses of the nodes because docker provides an abstraction and manages service discovery for you as well.

The solution with IP routing wouldn&#39;t work as you think because of [routing mesh][1]. All requests get load balanced without consideration of the node that gets the traffic. You can visit IP1 and due to routing mesh IP2 can process the request.

What do you want is to refer to your site as the DNS record you&#39;ve defined as a service name. 

Like this

```javascript
upstream site1_nginx  {
    server site1:80;
}
```

`site1` is the service name defined in `docker-compose.yml` (nginx has the DNS name as `nginx`).

You can refer to the service as particular replica but then you need to implement health check by yourself.

```javascript
upstream site1_nginx  {
    server site1.1:80;
    server site1.2:80;
    server site1.3:80;
}
```

  [1]: https://docs.docker.com/engine/swarm/ingress/

