answers.body_markdown:
The `name` variable exists in the TS file and you use it in the template. If the variable does not exist in the TS file and you are using it in `[(ngModel)]`, it throws an error.

    [(ngModel)]=&quot;name&quot;

`[(ngModel)]` it&#39;s called two-way data binding. If you change the value in the Template, it&#39;s changed in the TS and vice versa.

Two-way data binding is the fundamental future of Angular.

Here is how it works:

    &lt;input [(ngModel)]=&quot;name&quot;&gt;
    
    &lt;p&gt;Hello {{name}}!&lt;/p&gt; 

If you input a value, you can see it immediately in the paragraph. And if you change the value for name variable in TS, then you can see it in the input and in the paragraph.

`[()]` This makes it two-way data binding.

