Welcome to Stackoverflow!

Using `.count()` would be one way to check for the existence of the record before you add it. See the below function `countTypeNameRec` as an example of that.  

The below function `addTypeNameRec` then puts the count &amp; insert together, first checking the count of records, then if it&#39;s zero, adding the record.

See [the Knex .count() reference][1] for additional details about using `.count()`. (For large unindexed tables, using `select * where xxx limit 1` would probably be a better performance choice.)

**A Second Method:**
I assume that it&#39;s a hard rule that you can&#39;t have &#39;type&#39; table records with duplicate &#39;type_name&#39; field values. If that&#39;s the case, then making that field a primary key via your SQL table definition in your db (or creating a unique index on the table for the field) will also prevent users from creating duplicate records. In that case the `.insert()` statement will throw an error on a duplicate record. But it is a little messy to interpret the error if you want to give the user an understandable &#39;Value already exists&#39; error message. [Here][2] is a discussion on that issue.

If you don&#39;t care about returning the user an ugly raw database error which they probably won&#39;t understand, then you can use this second method in a simplistic fashion and just call the `insertTypeNameRec` function from the routing code instead of the `addTypeNameRec` function (skipping the count check).


**The Code**

    // count the records
    //
    function countTypeNameRec(input_type_name) {
  	   return db(&#39;types&#39;)
		.count(&#39;*&#39;)
		.where(&#39;type_name&#39;, input_type_name)
		.then((data)=&gt;{
				return data[0].count
  			})
    }

    // insert a new record
    //
    function insertTypeNameRec(input_type_name) {
  	   return db(&#39;types&#39;)
		.insert({type_name: input_type_name})
    }

    // Combine the count &amp; insert - the real goal
    //
    function addTypeNameRec(input_type_name) {

	   return countTypeNameRec(input_type_name)
	 	 .then((rec_count) =&gt; {
			if (rec_count===0) {
				insertTypeNameRec(input_type_name) 
			} else {
				// we can return an already exists error from here
			}
		 })
    }

    // Web routing code
    //
    router.post(&#39;/additem&#39;, function(req, res, next){

	   const input_type_name = req.body.getypename;
	   // we could validate our input here

       // for simplistic second method - call insertTypeNameRec() here instead
	   return addTypeNameRec(input_type_name)
		  .then(()=&gt;{
     			res.redirect(&#39;/additem?success=1&#39;)
  		   })
		   .catch((err)=&gt;{ 
				res.redirect(&#39;/additem?&#39;+err) 
		   })
	})

    // disclaimer: this code has not been tested

**A Freebie** (i.e. comments on things you didn&#39;t ask about) ... I tend to try to separate my capabilities into the smallest pieces/functions that I can. Then it becomes super simple to troubleshoot and test each piece. I especially try to separate the code at the database &amp; communications tiers. Then it&#39;s easy to stub out the web requests, and test them separately from the other server processing.


  [1]: http://knexjs.org/#Builder-count
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/52684205/where-can-i-find-documentation-for-the-types-of-knex-errors/52753070#52753070

